    News Review for mulesoft

    MuleSoft News Review

    Executive Summary

    MuleSoft's role within Salesforce's ecosystem has evolved substantially as the company positions the integration platform as critical infrastructure for its "agentic enterprise" strategy, with new capabilities including Agent Script for deterministic AI agent outcomes and Agent Fabric for multi-vendor agent orchestration announced at Dreamforce (Forrester). The integration platform has been incorporated into Salesforce's Data 360 unified data foundation alongside Data Cloud, Tableau, and the pending Informatica acquisition, serving as the "governed bridge" connecting AI agents to legacy systems of record (SiliconAngle). MuleSoft now functions within what Salesforce terms an "intelligent integration fabric" with enhanced security capabilities including mutual Transport Layer Security (mTLS) authentication for Salesforce integrations, while also supporting the beta launch of Hosted Model Context Protocol (MCP) Servers that enable AI agents to access Salesforce data across enterprise departments without custom coding, with General Availability targeted for February 2026 (Salesforce Developer). Market research firms have recognized MuleSoft as a key player in both the AI integration platforms market, projected to grow by $40.90 billion from 2024 to 2029 with a 32.6% CAGR, and the AI-enhanced RPA market expected to expand by $14.28 billion with a 33% CAGR (Globe Newswire).

    Key Developments

    Product Launches and Enhancements: - Launch of Agent Script capability for bringing deterministic outcomes through rules for AI agents, though analysts noted limitations for complex tasks (Forrester) - Introduction of Agent Fabric leveraging MuleSoft's API management capabilities to provide cataloging, governance, agent orchestration, and runtime visibility across all agents, working with both Salesforce and third-party platforms (Forrester) - Beta release of Salesforce Hosted MCP Servers integrating with MuleSoft to enable AI agents to access Salesforce data across enterprise departments, with General Availability targeted for February 2026 (Salesforce Developer) - Enhanced Salesforce Connector with mutual Transport Layer Security (mTLS) authentication capabilities to address security challenges in dynamic cloud environments (Salesforce Developer)

    Strategic Integration: - Integration into Salesforce's Data 360 unified data foundation alongside Data Cloud, Tableau, and Informatica acquisition (SiliconAngle) - Evolution into what Salesforce calls an "intelligent integration fabric" with unified control plane through Anypoint Flexible Gateway (SiliconAngle)

    Market Context

    MuleSoft's developments occur within a broader enterprise transformation toward AI-driven automation and agentic workflows. The integration platform market is experiencing substantial growth, with AI integration platforms projected to expand by $40.90 billion from 2024 to 2029 at a 32.6% CAGR (Globe Newswire). The shift from traditional task-based automation to orchestrated AI agent collaboration positions integration platforms like MuleSoft as foundational infrastructure rather than point solutions. Enterprise adoption of zero-trust security architecture and cloud-native authentication mechanisms drives demand for enhanced security features like mTLS authentication, particularly as organizations move to dynamic cloud environments where traditional IP allowlisting becomes operationally burdensome.

    Notable Quotes

    Rahul Auradkar, Executive Vice President and General Manager of Unified Data Services at Salesforce: "We have built Data 360 from the ground up on standards we are an open and extensible platform. That sort of an ecosystem vibrancy is needed for data fluidity that allows us to provide intelligent context in the moment." (SiliconAngle)

    Rahul Auradkar, Executive Vice President and General Manager of Unified Data Services at Salesforce: "We can have data integration and app integration now learn from each other for our customers. You get significant value for our customers across understanding, transparency and also with the governance." (SiliconAngle)

    Todd Lohr, Head of Ecosystems and National Operations Leader for Advisory Markets at KPMG U.S.: "You have the announcements they made this year with Informatica. We just did a session earlier today on Informatica and being able to get your data governance right, being able to get your data quality right, so that you can feed that into Salesforce and Agentforce. [Being] able to build those agents is going to be key." (SiliconAngle)

    Strategic Implications

    MuleSoft's strategic position has shifted from standalone integration platform to essential infrastructure within Salesforce's agentic enterprise architecture. The platform's evolution into an "intelligent integration fabric" positions it as the nervous system connecting AI agents to enterprise data and legacy systems, potentially expanding its total addressable market beyond traditional API management. However, analyst feedback indicates limitations in complex scenario handling, suggesting MuleSoft must enhance its capabilities to fully support Salesforce's agentic enterprise vision. The integration with emerging standards like Model Context Protocol and enhanced security features demonstrates adaptation to AI-driven workflows and zero-trust security requirements. Market recognition in both AI integration platforms and RPA sectors validates MuleSoft's relevance in the evolving automation landscape, though competition from cloud-native alternatives and hyperscaler platforms requires continued innovation to maintain differentiation.

    Article 7: Salesforce Hosted MCP Servers Are in Beta Today

    Source: View Full Article

    Summary

    Salesforce launched beta Hosted MCP Servers that integrate with MuleSoft to enable AI agents across enterprise departments to access Salesforce data through natural language without custom coding. The capability, built on Anthropic's open MCP standard, allows organizations to expose Salesforce APIs with enterprise-grade security and targets General Availability in February 2026. This positions MuleSoft within Salesforce's broader AI agent connectivity strategy, extending its integration capabilities beyond traditional APIs into the emerging AI interoperability market where agents can access CRM data for finance, legal, operations, and other departmental workflows.

    Article 8: Enhance Integration Security with mTLS for Salesforce and MuleSoft

    Source: View Full Article

    Summary

    MuleSoft has enhanced its Salesforce Connector with mutual Transport Layer Security (mTLS) authentication capabilities, addressing security challenges in cloud environments where traditional IP allowlisting becomes operationally burdensome due to regularly changing IP addresses in Salesforce's Hyperforce infrastructure. The implementation requires Java keystore files configured through Anypoint Studio and supports OAuth 2.0 JWT bearer flow authentication, positioning MuleSoft as offering cloud-native security solutions that align with zero-trust architecture principles while reducing operational overhead for enterprise customers managing dynamic cloud integrations.
